Name: War of the Straits
Description: 1354 – War of the Straits: The Genoese fleet under Paganino Doria defeats and captures the entire Venetian fleet under Niccolò Pisani at the Battle of Sapienza.

Name: Armagnac–Burgundian Civil War
Description: 1429 – Armagnac–Burgundian Civil War: Joan of Arc liberates Saint-Pierre-le-Moûtier.

Name: Christopher Columbus
Description: 1493 – Christopher Columbus reaches the Leeward Islands.

Name: Catherine of Aragon
Description: 1501 – Catherine of Aragon (later Henry VIII's first wife) meets Arthur Tudor, Henry VIII's older brother – they would later marry.

Name: Eighty Years' War
Description: 1576 – Eighty Years' War: In Flanders, Spain captures Antwerp (which is nearly destroyed after three days).

Name: Mary II of England
Description: 1677 – The future Mary II of England marries William, Prince of Orange; they later jointly reign as William and Mary.

Name: Teatro di San Carlo
Description: 1737 – The Teatro di San Carlo, the oldest working opera house in Europe, is inaugurated in Naples, Italy.

Name: Rebellion of Túpac Amaru II
Description: 1780 – The Rebellion of Túpac Amaru II against Spanish rule in the Viceroyalty of Peru begins.

Name: Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart
Description: 1783 – Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart's Symphony No. 36 is performed for the first time in Linz, Austria.

Name: Northwest Indian War
Description: 1791 – Northwest Indian War: The Western Confederacy of American Indians wins a major victory over the United States in the Battle of the Wabash.

Name: Russo-Ottoman siege
Description: 1798 – The Russo-Ottoman siege of Corfu begins.

Name: Newport Rising
Description: 1839 – Newport Rising: The last large-scale armed rebellion against authority in mainland Britain.

Name: James Young Simpson
Description: 1847 – Sir James Young Simpson, a Scottish physician, discovers the anaesthetic properties of chloroform.

Name: Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour
Description: 1852 – Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour, becomes the prime minister of Piedmont-Sardinia, which soon expands to become Italy.

Name: American Civil War
Description: 1864 – American Civil War: Confederate troops bombard a Union supply base and destroy millions of dollars in materiel at the Battle of Johnsonville.

Name: Camagüey
Description: 1868 – Camagüey, Cuba, revolts against Spain during the Ten Years' War.

Name: City and South London Railway
Description: 1890 – City and South London Railway: London's first deep-level tube railway opens between King William Street and Stockwell.

Name: World War I
Description: 1918 – World War I: The Armistice of Villa Giusti between Italy and Austria-Hungary is implemented.

Name: Nazi Party
Description: 1921 – The Saalschutz Abteilung (hall defense detachment) of the Nazi Party is renamed the Sturmabteilung (storm detachment) after a large riot in Munich.

Name: Japanese prime minister
Description: 1921   – Japanese prime minister Hara Takashi is assassinated in Tokyo.

Name: Howard Carter
Description: 1922 – In Egypt, British archaeologist Howard Carter and his men find the entrance to Tutankhamun's tomb in the Valley of the Kings.

Name: Nellie Tayloe Ross
Description: 1924 – Nellie Tayloe Ross of Wyoming becomes the first female elected as governor in the United States.

Name: Spanish Civil War
Description: 1936 – Spanish Civil War: Largo Caballero reshuffles his war cabinet, persuading the anarcho-syndicalist CNT to join the government.

Name: World War II
Description: 1939 – World War II: U.S. president Franklin D. Roosevelt orders the United States Customs Service to implement the Neutrality Act of 1939, allowing cash-and-carry purchases of weapons by belligerents.

Name: Adolf Hitler
Description: 1942 – World War II: Disobeying a direct order by Adolf Hitler, General Field Marshal Erwin Rommel begins a retreat of his forces after a costly defeat during the Second Battle of El Alamein. The retreat would ultimately last five months.

Name: 7th Macedonian Liberation Brigade
Description: 1944 – World War II: The 7th Macedonian Liberation Brigade liberates Bitola for the Allies.

Name: Operation Pheasant
Description: 1944   – World War II: Operation Pheasant, an Allied offensive to liberate North Brabant in the Netherlands, ends successfully.

Name: United States government
Description: 1952 – The United States government establishes the National Security Agency, or NSA.

Name: Soviet
Description: 1956 – Soviet troops enter Hungary to end the Hungarian revolution against the Soviet Union that started on October 23. Thousands are killed, more are wounded, and nearly a quarter million leave the country.

Name: Kasakela Chimpanzee Community
Description: 1960 – At the Kasakela Chimpanzee Community in Tanzania, Jane Goodall observes chimpanzees creating tools, the first-ever observation in non-human animals.

Name: Operation Fishbowl
Description: 1962 – The United States concludes Operation Fishbowl, its final above-ground nuclear weapons testing series, in anticipation of the 1963 Partial Nuclear Test Ban Treaty.

Name: Arno River
Description: 1966 – The Arno River floods Florence, Italy, to a maximum depth of 6.7 m (22 ft), leaving thousands homeless and destroying millions of masterpieces of art and rare books. Venice is also submerged on the same day at its record all-time acqua alta of 194 cm (76 in).

Name: Iberia Flight 062
Description: 1967 – Iberia Flight 062 crashes in Blackdown, West Sussex, killing all 37 people on board including British actress June Thorburn.

Name: Vietnam War
Description: 1970 – Vietnam War: The United States turns over control of the air base at Bình Thủy in the Mekong Delta to South Vietnam.

Name: Salvador Allende
Description: 1970   – Salvador Allende takes office as President of Chile, the first Marxist to become president of a Latin American country through open elections.

Name: 1973 oil crisis
Description: 1973 – The Netherlands experiences the first car-free Sunday caused by the 1973 oil crisis. Highways are used only by cyclists and roller skaters.

Name: Iran hostage crisis
Description: 1979 – Iran hostage crisis: A group of Iranian college students overruns the U.S. embassy in Tehran and takes 90 hostages.

Name: Ronald Reagan
Description: 1980 – Ronald Reagan is elected as the 40th President of the United States, defeating incumbent Jimmy Carter.

Name: China Airlines Flight 605
Description: 1993 – China Airlines Flight 605, a brand-new 747-400, overruns the runway at Hong Kong Kai Tak Airport.

Name: Israel-Palestinian conflict
Description: 1995 – Israel-Palestinian conflict: Israeli prime minister Yitzhak Rabin is assassinated by an extremist Israeli.

Name: He Depu
Description: 2002 – Chinese authorities arrest cyber-dissident He Depu for signing a pro-democracy letter to the 16th Communist Party Congress.

Name: Barack Obama
Description: 2008 – Barack Obama becomes the first person of biracial or African-American descent to be elected as President of the United States.

Name: Aero Caribbean Flight 883
Description: 2010 – Aero Caribbean Flight 883 crashes into Guasimal, Sancti Spíritus; all 68 passengers and crew are killed.

Name: Qantas Flight 32
Description: 2010   – Qantas Flight 32, an Airbus A380, suffers an uncontained engine failure over Indonesia shortly after taking off from Singapore, crippling the jet. The crew manage to safely return to Singapore, saving all 469 passengers and crew.

Name: crashes
Description: 2015 – A cargo plane crashes shortly after takeoff from Juba International Airport in Juba, South Sudan, killing at least 37 people.

Name: collapses
Description: 2015   – A building collapses in the Pakistani city of Lahore resulting in at least 45 deaths and at least 100 injuries.

Name: Tigray War
Description: 2020 – The Tigray War begins with Tigrayan rebels launching attacks on Ethiopian command centers.

Name: Khash massacre
Description: 2022 – The Khash massacre, which refers to the repression of protesters by Iranian security forces, resulting in 18 deaths and more than 20 injuries.
